## Displaying Lint Output in the Editor\par
\par
> Note: this feature is available with `react-scripts@0.2.0` and higher.<br>\par
> It also only works with npm 3 or higher.\par
\par
Some editors, including Sublime Text, Atom, and Visual Studio Code, provide plugins for ESLint.\par
\par
They are not required for linting. You should see the linter output right in your terminal as well as the browser console. However, if you prefer the lint results to appear right in your editor, there are some extra steps you can do.\par
\par
You would need to install an ESLint plugin for your editor first. Then, add a file called `.eslintrc` to the project root:\par
\par
```js\par
\{\par
  "extends": "react-app"\par
\}\par
```\par
\par
Now your editor should report the linting warnings.\par
\par
Note that even if you edit your `.eslintrc` file further, these changes will **only affect the editor integration**. They won\rquote t affect the terminal and in-browser lint output. This is because Create React App intentionally provides a minimal set of rules that find common mistakes.\par
\par
If you want to enforce a coding style for your project, consider using [Prettier](https://github.com/jlongster/prettier) instead of ESLint style rules.\par
