## Formatting Code Automatically\par
\par
Prettier is an opinionated code formatter with support for JavaScript, CSS and JSON. With Prettier you can format the code you write automatically to ensure a code style within your project. See the [Prettier's GitHub page](https://github.com/prettier/prettier) for more information, and look at this [page to see it in action](https://prettier.github.io/prettier/).\par
\par
To format our code whenever we make a commit in git, we need to install the following dependencies:\par
\par
```sh\par
npm install --save husky lint-staged prettier\par
```\par
\par
Alternatively you may use `yarn`:\par
\par
```sh\par
yarn add husky lint-staged prettier\par
```\par
\par
- `husky` makes it easy to use githooks as if they are npm scripts.\par
- `lint-staged` allows us to run scripts on staged files in git. See this [blog post about lint-staged to learn more about it](https://medium.com/@okonetchnikov/make-linting-great-again-f3890e1ad6b8).\par
- `prettier` is the JavaScript formatter we will run before commits.\par
\par
Now we can make sure every file is formatted correctly by adding a few lines to the `package.json` in the project root.\par
\par
Add the following field to the `package.json` section:\par
\par
```diff\par
+  "husky": \{\par
+    "hooks": \{\par
+      "pre-commit": "lint-staged"\par
+    \}\par
+  \}\par
```\par
\par
Next we add a 'lint-staged' field to the `package.json`, for example:\par
\par
```diff\par
  "dependencies": \{\par
    // ...\par
  \},\par
+ "lint-staged": \{\par
+   "src/**/*.\{js,jsx,json,css\}": [\par
+     "prettier --single-quote --write",\par
+     "git add"\par
+   ]\par
+ \},\par
  "scripts": \{\par
```\par
\par
Now, whenever you make a commit, Prettier will format the changed files automatically. You can also run `./node_modules/.bin/prettier --single-quote --write "src/**/*.\{js,jsx\}"` to format your entire project for the first time.\par
\par
Next you might want to integrate Prettier in your favorite editor. Read the section on [Editor Integration](https://prettier.io/docs/en/editors.html) on the Prettier GitHub page.\par
