## Importing a Component\par
\par
This project setup supports ES6 modules thanks to Webpack.<br>\par
While you can still use `require()` and `module.exports`, we encourage you to use [`import` and `export`](http://exploringjs.com/es6/ch_modules.html) instead.\par
\par
For example:\par
\par
### `Button.js`\par
\par
```js\par
import React, \{ Component \} from 'react';\par
\par
class Button extends Component \{\par
  render() \{\par
    // ...\par
  \}\par
\}\par
\par
export default Button; // Don\rquote t forget to use export default!\par
```\par
\par
### `DangerButton.js`\par
\par
```js\par
import React, \{ Component \} from 'react';\par
import Button from './Button'; // Import a component from another file\par
\par
class DangerButton extends Component \{\par
  render() \{\par
    return <Button color="red" />;\par
  \}\par
\}\par
\par
export default DangerButton;\par
```\par
\par
Be aware of the [difference between default and named exports](http://stackoverflow.com/questions/36795819/react-native-es-6-when-should-i-use-curly-braces-for-import/36796281#36796281). It is a common source of mistakes.\par
\par
We suggest that you stick to using default imports and exports when a module only exports a single thing (for example, a component). That\rquote s what you get when you use `export default Button` and `import Button from './Button'`.\par
\par
Named exports are useful for utility modules that export several functions. A module may have at most one default export and as many named exports as you like.\par
\par
Learn more about ES6 modules:\par
\par
- [When to use the curly braces?](http://stackoverflow.com/questions/36795819/react-native-es-6-when-should-i-use-curly-braces-for-import/36796281#36796281)\par
- [Exploring ES6: Modules](http://exploringjs.com/es6/ch_modules.html)\par
- [Understanding ES6: Modules](https://leanpub.com/understandinges6/read#leanpub-auto-encapsulating-code-with-modules)\par
