## Code Splitting\par
\par
Instead of downloading the entire app before users can use it, code splitting allows you to split your code into small chunks which you can then load on demand.\par
\par
This project setup supports code splitting via [dynamic `import()`](http://2ality.com/2017/01/import-operator.html#loading-code-on-demand). Its [proposal](https://github.com/tc39/proposal-dynamic-import) is in stage 3. The `import()` function-like form takes the module name as an argument and returns a [`Promise`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Promise) which always resolves to the namespace object of the module.\par
\par
Here is an example:\par
\par
### `moduleA.js`\par
\par
```js\par
const moduleA = 'Hello';\par
\par
export \{ moduleA \};\par
```\par
\par
### `App.js`\par
\par
```js\par
import React, \{ Component \} from 'react';\par
\par
class App extends Component \{\par
  handleClick = () => \{\par
    import('./moduleA')\par
      .then((\{ moduleA \}) => \{\par
        // Use moduleA\par
      \})\par
      .catch(err => \{\par
        // Handle failure\par
      \});\par
  \};\par
\par
  render() \{\par
    return (\par
      <div>\par
        <button onClick=\{this.handleClick\}>Load</button>\par
      </div>\par
    );\par
  \}\par
\}\par
\par
export default App;\par
```\par
\par
This will make `moduleA.js` and all its unique dependencies as a separate chunk that only loads after the user clicks the 'Load' button.\par
\par
You can also use it with `async` / `await` syntax if you prefer it.\par
\par
### With React Router\par
\par
If you are using React Router check out [this tutorial](http://serverless-stack.com/chapters/code-splitting-in-create-react-app.html) on how to use code splitting with it. You can find the companion GitHub repository [here](https://github.com/AnomalyInnovations/serverless-stack-demo-client/tree/code-splitting-in-create-react-app).\par
\par
Also check out the [Code Splitting](https://reactjs.org/docs/code-splitting.html) section in React documentation.\par
