## Adding a Stylesheet\par
\par
This project setup uses [Webpack](https://webpack.js.org/) for handling all assets. Webpack offers a custom way of \ldblquote extending\rdblquote  the concept of `import` beyond JavaScript. To express that a JavaScript file depends on a CSS file, you need to **import the CSS from the JavaScript file**:\par
\par
### `Button.css`\par
\par
```css\par
.Button \{\par
  padding: 20px;\par
\}\par
```\par
\par
### `Button.js`\par
\par
```js\par
import React, \{ Component \} from 'react';\par
import './Button.css'; // Tell Webpack that Button.js uses these styles\par
\par
class Button extends Component \{\par
  render() \{\par
    // You can use them as regular CSS styles\par
    return <div className="Button" />;\par
  \}\par
\}\par
```\par
\par
**This is not required for React** but many people find this feature convenient. You can read about the benefits of this approach [here](https://medium.com/seek-blog/block-element-modifying-your-javascript-components-d7f99fcab52b). However you should be aware that this makes your code less portable to other build tools and environments than Webpack.\par
\par
In development, expressing dependencies this way allows your styles to be reloaded on the fly as you edit them. In production, all CSS files will be concatenated into a single minified `.css` file in the build output.\par
\par
If you are concerned about using Webpack-specific semantics, you can put all your CSS right into `src/index.css`. It would still be imported from `src/index.js`, but you could always remove that import if you later migrate to a different build tool.\par
\par
## Adding a CSS Modules Stylesheet\par
\par
> Note: this feature is available with `react-scripts@2.0.0` and higher.\par
\par
This project supports [CSS Modules](https://github.com/css-modules/css-modules) alongside regular stylesheets using the `[name].module.css` file naming convention. CSS Modules allows the scoping of CSS by automatically creating a unique classname of the format `[filename]\\_[classname]\\_\\_[hash]`.\par
\par
> **Tip:** Should you want to preprocess a stylesheet with Sass then make sure to [follow the installation instructions](#adding-a-sass-stylesheet) and then change the stylesheet file extension as follows: `[name].module.scss` or `[name].module.sass`.\par
\par
CSS Modules let you use the same CSS class name in different files without worrying about naming clashes. Learn more about CSS Modules [here](https://css-tricks.com/css-modules-part-1-need/).\par
\par
### `Button.module.css`\par
\par
```css\par
.error \{\par
  background-color: red;\par
\}\par
```\par
\par
### `another-stylesheet.css`\par
\par
```css\par
.error \{\par
  color: red;\par
\}\par
```\par
\par
### `Button.js`\par
\par
```js\par
import React, \{ Component \} from 'react';\par
import styles from './Button.module.css'; // Import css modules stylesheet as styles\par
import './another-stylesheet.css'; // Import regular stylesheet\par
\par
class Button extends Component \{\par
  render() \{\par
    // reference as a js object\par
    return <button className=\{styles.error\}>Error Button</button>;\par
  \}\par
\}\par
```\par
\par
### Result\par
\par
No clashes from other `.error` class names\par
\par
```html\par
<!-- This button has red background but not red text -->\par
<button class="Button_error_ax7yz"></div>\par
```\par
\par
**This is an optional feature.** Regular `<link>` stylesheets and CSS files are fully supported. CSS Modules are turned on for files ending with the `.module.css` extension.\par
\par
## Adding a Sass Stylesheet\par
\par
> Note: this feature is available with `react-scripts@2.0.0` and higher.\par
\par
Generally, we recommend that you don\rquote t reuse the same CSS classes across different components. For example, instead of using a `.Button` CSS class in `<AcceptButton>` and `<RejectButton>` components, we recommend creating a `<Button>` component with its own `.Button` styles, that both `<AcceptButton>` and `<RejectButton>` can render (but [not inherit](https://facebook.github.io/react/docs/composition-vs-inheritance.html)).\par
\par
Following this rule often makes CSS preprocessors less useful, as features like mixins and nesting are replaced by component composition. You can, however, integrate a CSS preprocessor if you find it valuable.\par
\par
To use Sass, first install `node-sass`:\par
\par
```bash\par
$ npm install node-sass --save\par
$ # or\par
$ yarn add node-sass\par
```\par
\par
Now you can rename `src/App.css` to `src/App.scss` and update `src/App.js` to import `src/App.scss`.\par
This file and any other file will be automatically compiled if imported with the extension `.scss` or `.sass`.\par
\par
To share variables between Sass files, you can use Sass imports. For example, `src/App.scss` and other component style files could include `@import "./shared.scss";` with variable definitions.\par
\par
This will allow you to do imports like\par
\par
```scss\par
@import 'styles/_colors.scss'; // assuming a styles directory under src/\par
@import '~nprogress/nprogress'; // importing a css file from the nprogress node module\par
```\par
\par
> **Tip:** You can opt into using this feature with [CSS modules](#adding-a-css-modules-stylesheet) too!\par
\par
> **Note:** You must prefix imports from `node_modules` with `~` as displayed above.\par
\par
## Post-Processing CSS\par
\par
This project setup minifies your CSS and adds vendor prefixes to it automatically through [Autoprefixer](https://github.com/postcss/autoprefixer) so you don\rquote t need to worry about it.\par
\par
Support for new CSS features like the [`all` property](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/all), [`break` properties](https://www.w3.org/TR/css-break-3/#breaking-controls), [custom properties](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/Using_CSS_variables), and [media query ranges](https://www.w3.org/TR/mediaqueries-4/#range-context) are automatically polyfilled to add support for older browsers.\par
\par
You can customize your target support browsers by adjusting the `browserslist` key in `package.json` accoring to the [Browserslist specification](https://github.com/browserslist/browserslist#readme).\par
\par
For example, this:\par
\par
```css\par
.App \{\par
  display: flex;\par
  flex-direction: row;\par
  align-items: center;\par
\}\par
```\par
\par
becomes this:\par
\par
```css\par
.App \{\par
  display: -webkit-box;\par
  display: -ms-flexbox;\par
  display: flex;\par
  -webkit-box-orient: horizontal;\par
  -webkit-box-direction: normal;\par
  -ms-flex-direction: row;\par
  flex-direction: row;\par
  -webkit-box-align: center;\par
  -ms-flex-align: center;\par
  align-items: center;\par
\}\par
```\par
\par
If you need to disable autoprefixing for some reason, [follow this section](https://github.com/postcss/autoprefixer#disabling).\par
\par
[CSS Grid Layout](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/CSS_Grid_Layout) prefixing is disabled by default, but it will **not** strip manual prefixing.\par
If you'd like to opt-in to CSS Grid prefixing, [first familiarize yourself about its limitations](https://github.com/postcss/autoprefixer#does-autoprefixer-polyfill-grid-layout-for-ie).<br>\par
To enable CSS Grid prefixing, add `/* autoprefixer grid: on */` to the top of your CSS file.\par
\par
## Adding Images, Fonts, and Files\par
\par
With Webpack, using static assets like images and fonts works similarly to CSS.\par
\par
You can **`import` a file right in a JavaScript module**. This tells Webpack to include that file in the bundle. Unlike CSS imports, importing a file gives you a string value. This value is the final path you can reference in your code, e.g. as the `src` attribute of an image or the `href` of a link to a PDF.\par
\par
To reduce the number of requests to the server, importing images that are less than 10,000 bytes returns a [data URI](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Basics_of_HTTP/Data_URIs) instead of a path. This applies to the following file extensions: bmp, gif, jpg, jpeg, and png. SVG files are excluded due to [#1153](https://github.com/facebook/create-react-app/issues/1153).\par
\par
Here is an example:\par
\par
```js\par
import React from 'react';\par
import logo from './logo.png'; // Tell Webpack this JS file uses this image\par
\par
console.log(logo); // /logo.84287d09.png\par
\par
function Header() \{\par
  // Import result is the URL of your image\par
  return <img src=\{logo\} alt="Logo" />;\par
\}\par
\par
export default Header;\par
```\par
\par
This ensures that when the project is built, Webpack will correctly move the images into the build folder, and provide us with correct paths.\par
\par
This works in CSS too:\par
\par
```css\par
.Logo \{\par
  background-image: url(./logo.png);\par
\}\par
```\par
\par
Webpack finds all relative module references in CSS (they start with `./`) and replaces them with the final paths from the compiled bundle. If you make a typo or accidentally delete an important file, you will see a compilation error, just like when you import a non-existent JavaScript module. The final filenames in the compiled bundle are generated by Webpack from content hashes. If the file content changes in the future, Webpack will give it a different name in production so you don\rquote t need to worry about long-term caching of assets.\par
\par
Please be advised that this is also a custom feature of Webpack.\par
\par
**It is not required for React** but many people enjoy it (and React Native uses a similar mechanism for images).<br>\par
An alternative way of handling static assets is described in the next section.\par
\par
### Adding SVGs\par
\par
> Note: this feature is available with `react-scripts@2.0.0` and higher.\par
\par
One way to add SVG files was described in the section above. You can also import SVGs directly as React components. You can use either of the two approaches. In your code it would look like this:\par
\par
```js\par
import \{ ReactComponent as Logo \} from './logo.svg';\par
const App = () => (\par
  <div>\par
    \{/* Logo is an actual React component */\}\par
    <Logo />\par
  </div>\par
);\par
```\par
\par
This is handy if you don't want to load SVG as a separate file. Don't forget the curly braces in the import! The `ReactComponent` import name is special and tells Create React App that you want a React component that renders an SVG, rather than its filename.\par
\par
## Using the `public` Folder\par
\par
> Note: this feature is available with `react-scripts@0.5.0` and higher.\par
\par
### Changing the HTML\par
\par
The `public` folder contains the HTML file so you can tweak it, for example, to [set the page title](#changing-the-page-title).\par
The `<script>` tag with the compiled code will be added to it automatically during the build process.\par
\par
### Adding Assets Outside of the Module System\par
\par
You can also add other assets to the `public` folder.\par
\par
Note that we normally encourage you to `import` assets in JavaScript files instead.\par
For example, see the sections on [adding a stylesheet](#adding-a-stylesheet) and [adding images and fonts](#adding-images-fonts-and-files).\par
This mechanism provides a number of benefits:\par
\par
- Scripts and stylesheets get minified and bundled together to avoid extra network requests.\par
- Missing files cause compilation errors instead of 404 errors for your users.\par
- Result filenames include content hashes so you don\rquote t need to worry about browsers caching their old versions.\par
\par
However there is an **escape hatch** that you can use to add an asset outside of the module system.\par
\par
If you put a file into the `public` folder, it will **not** be processed by Webpack. Instead it will be copied into the build folder untouched. To reference assets in the `public` folder, you need to use a special variable called `PUBLIC_URL`.\par
\par
Inside `index.html`, you can use it like this:\par
\par
```html\par
<link rel="shortcut icon" href="%PUBLIC_URL%/favicon.ico">\par
```\par
\par
Only files inside the `public` folder will be accessible by `%PUBLIC_URL%` prefix. If you need to use a file from `src` or `node_modules`, you\rquote ll have to copy it there to explicitly specify your intention to make this file a part of the build.\par
\par
When you run `npm run build`, Create React App will substitute `%PUBLIC_URL%` with a correct absolute path so your project works even if you use client-side routing or host it at a non-root URL.\par
\par
In JavaScript code, you can use `process.env.PUBLIC_URL` for similar purposes:\par
\par
```js\par
render() \{\par
  // Note: this is an escape hatch and should be used sparingly!\par
  // Normally we recommend using `import` for getting asset URLs\par
  // as described in \ldblquote Adding Images and Fonts\rdblquote  above this section.\par
  return <img src=\{process.env.PUBLIC_URL + '/img/logo.png'\} />;\par
\}\par
```\par
\par
Keep in mind the downsides of this approach:\par
\par
- None of the files in `public` folder get post-processed or minified.\par
- Missing files will not be called at compilation time, and will cause 404 errors for your users.\par
- Result filenames won\rquote t include content hashes so you\rquote ll need to add query arguments or rename them every time they change.\par
\par
### When to Use the `public` Folder\par
\par
Normally we recommend importing [stylesheets](#adding-a-stylesheet), [images, and fonts](#adding-images-fonts-and-files) from JavaScript.\par
The `public` folder is useful as a workaround for a number of less common cases:\par
\par
- You need a file with a specific name in the build output, such as [`manifest.webmanifest`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/Manifest).\par
- You have thousands of images and need to dynamically reference their paths.\par
- You want to include a small script like [`pace.js`](http://github.hubspot.com/pace/docs/welcome/) outside of the bundled code.\par
- Some library may be incompatible with Webpack and you have no other option but to include it as a `<script>` tag.\par
\par
Note that if you add a `<script>` that declares global variables, you also need to read the next section on using them.\par
\par
## Using Global Variables\par
\par
When you include a script in the HTML file that defines global variables and try to use one of these variables in the code, the linter will complain because it cannot see the definition of the variable.\par
\par
You can avoid this by reading the global variable explicitly from the `window` object, for example:\par
\par
```js\par
const $ = window.$;\par
```\par
\par
This makes it obvious you are using a global variable intentionally rather than because of a typo.\par
\par
Alternatively, you can force the linter to ignore any line by adding `// eslint-disable-line` after it.\par
\par
## Adding Bootstrap\par
\par
You don\rquote t have to use [reactstrap](https://reactstrap.github.io/) together with React but it is a popular library for integrating Bootstrap with React apps. If you need it, you can integrate it with Create React App by following these steps:\par
\par
Install reactstrap and Bootstrap from npm. reactstrap does not include Bootstrap CSS so this needs to be installed as well:\par
\par
```sh\par
npm install --save reactstrap bootstrap@4\par
```\par
\par
Alternatively you may use `yarn`:\par
\par
```sh\par
yarn add bootstrap@4 reactstrap\par
```\par
\par
Import Bootstrap CSS and optionally Bootstrap theme CSS in the beginning of your `src/index.js` file:\par
\par
```js\par
import 'bootstrap/dist/css/bootstrap.css';\par
// Put any other imports below so that CSS from your\par
// components takes precedence over default styles.\par
```\par
\par
Import required reactstrap components within `src/App.js` file or your custom component files:\par
\par
```js\par
import \{ Button \} from 'reactstrap';\par
```\par
\par
Now you are ready to use the imported reactstrap components within your component hierarchy defined in the render method. Here is an example [`App.js`](https://gist.githubusercontent.com/zx6658/d9f128cd57ca69e583ea2b5fea074238/raw/a56701c142d0c622eb6c20a457fbc01d708cb485/App.js) redone using reactstrap.\par
\par
### Using a Custom Theme\par
\par
> Note: this feature is available with `react-scripts@2.0.0` and higher.\par
\par
Sometimes you might need to tweak the visual styles of Bootstrap (or equivalent package).<br>\par
As of `react-scripts@2.0.0` you can import `.scss` files. This makes it possible to use a package's built-in Sass variables for global style preferences.\par
\par
To customize Bootstrap, create a file called `src/custom.scss` (or similar) and import the Bootstrap source stylesheet. Add any overrides _before_ the imported file(s). You can reference [Bootstrap's documentation](http://getbootstrap.com/docs/4.1/getting-started/theming/#css-variables) for the names of the available variables.\par
\par
```scss\par
// Override default variables before the import\par
$body-bg: #000;\par
\par
// Import Bootstrap and its default variables\par
@import '~bootstrap/scss/bootstrap.scss';\par
```\par
\par
> **Note:** You must prefix imports from `node_modules` with `~` as displayed above.\par
\par
Finally, import the newly created `.scss` file instead of the default Bootstrap `.css` in the beginning of your `src/index.js` file, for example:\par
\par
```javascript\par
import './custom.scss';\par
```\par
