## Adding Custom Environment Variables\par
\par
> Note: this feature is available with `react-scripts@0.2.3` and higher.\par
\par
Your project can consume variables declared in your environment as if they were declared locally in your JS files. By\par
default you will have `NODE_ENV` defined for you, and any other environment variables starting with\par
`REACT_APP_`.\par
\par
**The environment variables are embedded during the build time**. Since Create React App produces a static HTML/CSS/JS bundle, it can\rquote t possibly read them at runtime. To read them at runtime, you would need to load HTML into memory on the server and replace placeholders in runtime, just like [described here](#injecting-data-from-the-server-into-the-page). Alternatively you can rebuild the app on the server anytime you change them.\par
\par
> Note: You must create custom environment variables beginning with `REACT_APP_`. Any other variables except `NODE_ENV` will be ignored to avoid accidentally [exposing a private key on the machine that could have the same name](https://github.com/facebook/create-react-app/issues/865#issuecomment-252199527). Changing any environment variables will require you to restart the development server if it is running.\par
\par
These environment variables will be defined for you on `process.env`. For example, having an environment\par
variable named `REACT_APP_SECRET_CODE` will be exposed in your JS as `process.env.REACT_APP_SECRET_CODE`.\par
\par
There is also a special built-in environment variable called `NODE_ENV`. You can read it from `process.env.NODE_ENV`. When you run `npm start`, it is always equal to `'development'`, when you run `npm test` it is always equal to `'test'`, and when you run `npm run build` to make a production bundle, it is always equal to `'production'`. **You cannot override `NODE_ENV` manually.** This prevents developers from accidentally deploying a slow development build to production.\par
\par
These environment variables can be useful for displaying information conditionally based on where the project is\par
deployed or consuming sensitive data that lives outside of version control.\par
\par
First, you need to have environment variables defined. For example, let\rquote s say you wanted to consume a secret defined\par
in the environment inside a `<form>`:\par
\par
```jsx\par
render() \{\par
  return (\par
    <div>\par
      <small>You are running this application in <b>\{process.env.NODE_ENV\}</b> mode.</small>\par
      <form>\par
        <input type="hidden" defaultValue=\{process.env.REACT_APP_SECRET_CODE\} />\par
      </form>\par
    </div>\par
  );\par
\}\par
```\par
\par
During the build, `process.env.REACT_APP_SECRET_CODE` will be replaced with the current value of the `REACT_APP_SECRET_CODE` environment variable. Remember that the `NODE_ENV` variable will be set for you automatically.\par
\par
When you load the app in the browser and inspect the `<input>`, you will see its value set to `abcdef`, and the bold text will show the environment provided when using `npm start`:\par
\par
```html\par
<div>\par
  <small>You are running this application in <b>development</b> mode.</small>\par
  <form>\par
    <input type="hidden" value="abcdef" />\par
  </form>\par
</div>\par
```\par
\par
The above form is looking for a variable called `REACT_APP_SECRET_CODE` from the environment. In order to consume this\par
value, we need to have it defined in the environment. This can be done using two ways: either in your shell or in\par
a `.env` file. Both of these ways are described in the next few sections.\par
\par
Having access to the `NODE_ENV` is also useful for performing actions conditionally:\par
\par
```js\par
if (process.env.NODE_ENV !== 'production') \{\par
  analytics.disable();\par
\}\par
```\par
\par
When you compile the app with `npm run build`, the minification step will strip out this condition, and the resulting bundle will be smaller.\par
\par
### Referencing Environment Variables in the HTML\par
\par
> Note: this feature is available with `react-scripts@0.9.0` and higher.\par
\par
You can also access the environment variables starting with `REACT_APP_` in the `public/index.html`. For example:\par
\par
```html\par
<title>%REACT_APP_WEBSITE_NAME%</title>\par
```\par
\par
Note that the caveats from the above section apply:\par
\par
- Apart from a few built-in variables (`NODE_ENV` and `PUBLIC_URL`), variable names must start with `REACT_APP_` to work.\par
- The environment variables are injected at build time. If you need to inject them at runtime, [follow this approach instead](#generating-dynamic-meta-tags-on-the-server).\par
\par
### Adding Temporary Environment Variables In Your Shell\par
\par
Defining environment variables can vary between OSes. It\rquote s also important to know that this manner is temporary for the\par
life of the shell session.\par
\par
#### Windows (cmd.exe)\par
\par
```cmd\par
set "REACT_APP_SECRET_CODE=abcdef" && npm start\par
```\par
\par
(Note: Quotes around the variable assignment are required to avoid a trailing whitespace.)\par
\par
#### Windows (Powershell)\par
\par
```Powershell\par
($env:REACT_APP_SECRET_CODE = "abcdef") -and (npm start)\par
```\par
\par
#### Linux, macOS (Bash)\par
\par
```bash\par
REACT_APP_SECRET_CODE=abcdef npm start\par
```\par
\par
### Adding Development Environment Variables In `.env`\par
\par
> Note: this feature is available with `react-scripts@0.5.0` and higher.\par
\par
To define permanent environment variables, create a file called `.env` in the root of your project:\par
\par
```\par
REACT_APP_SECRET_CODE=abcdef\par
```\par
\par
> Note: You must create custom environment variables beginning with `REACT_APP_`. Any other variables except `NODE_ENV` will be ignored to avoid [accidentally exposing a private key on the machine that could have the same name](https://github.com/facebook/create-react-app/issues/865#issuecomment-252199527). Changing any environment variables will require you to restart the development server if it is running.\par
\par
`.env` files **should be** checked into source control (with the exclusion of `.env*.local`).\par
\par
#### What other `.env` files can be used?\par
\par
> Note: this feature is **available with `react-scripts@1.0.0` and higher**.\par
\par
- `.env`: Default.\par
- `.env.local`: Local overrides. **This file is loaded for all environments except test.**\par
- `.env.development`, `.env.test`, `.env.production`: Environment-specific settings.\par
- `.env.development.local`, `.env.test.local`, `.env.production.local`: Local overrides of environment-specific settings.\par
\par
Files on the left have more priority than files on the right:\par
\par
- `npm start`: `.env.development.local`, `.env.development`, `.env.local`, `.env`\par
- `npm run build`: `.env.production.local`, `.env.production`, `.env.local`, `.env`\par
