## Proxying API Requests in Development\par
\par
> Note: this feature is available with `react-scripts@0.2.3` and higher.\par
\par
People often serve the front-end React app from the same host and port as their backend implementation.<br>\par
For example, a production setup might look like this after the app is deployed:\par
\par
```\par
/             - static server returns index.html with React app\par
/todos        - static server returns index.html with React app\par
/api/todos    - server handles any /api/* requests using the backend implementation\par
```\par
\par
Such setup is **not** required. However, if you **do** have a setup like this, it is convenient to write requests like `fetch('/api/todos')` without worrying about redirecting them to another host or port during development.\par
\par
To tell the development server to proxy any unknown requests to your API server in development, add a `proxy` field to your `package.json`, for example:\par
\par
```js\par
  "proxy": "{{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK http://localhost:4000 }}{\fldrslt{http://localhost:4000\ul0\cf0}}}}\f1\fs22 ",\par
```\par
\par
This way, when you `fetch('/api/todos')` in development, the development server will recognize that it\rquote s not a static asset, and will proxy your request to `http://localhost:4000/api/todos` as a fallback. The development server will **only** attempt to send requests without `text/html` in its `Accept` header to the proxy.\par
\par
Conveniently, this avoids [CORS issues](http://stackoverflow.com/questions/21854516/understanding-ajax-cors-and-security-considerations) and error messages like this in development:\par
\par
```\par
Fetch API cannot load {{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK http://localhost:4000/api/todos }}{\fldrslt{http://localhost:4000/api/todos\ul0\cf0}}}}\f1\fs22 . No 'Access-Control-Allow-Origin' header is present on the requested resource. Origin '{{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK http://localhost:3000 }}{\fldrslt{http://localhost:3000\ul0\cf0}}}}\f1\fs22 ' is therefore not allowed access. If an opaque response serves your needs, set the request's mode to 'no-cors' to fetch the resource with CORS disabled.\par
```\par
\par
Keep in mind that `proxy` only has effect in development (with `npm start`), and it is up to you to ensure that URLs like `/api/todos` point to the right thing in production. You don\rquote t have to use the `/api` prefix. Any unrecognized request without a `text/html` accept header will be redirected to the specified `proxy`.\par
\par
The `proxy` option supports HTTP, HTTPS and WebSocket connections.<br>\par
If the `proxy` option is **not** flexible enough for you, alternatively you can:\par
\par
- [Configure the proxy yourself](#configuring-the-proxy-manually)\par
- Enable CORS on your server ([here\rquote s how to do it for Express](http://enable-cors.org/server_expressjs.html)).\par
- Use [environment variables](#adding-custom-environment-variables) to inject the right server host and port into your app.\par
\par
### "Invalid Host Header" Errors After Configuring Proxy\par
\par
When you enable the `proxy` option, you opt into a more strict set of host checks. This is necessary because leaving the backend open to remote hosts makes your computer vulnerable to DNS rebinding attacks. The issue is explained in [this article](https://medium.com/webpack/webpack-dev-server-middleware-security-issues-1489d950874a) and [this issue](https://github.com/webpack/webpack-dev-server/issues/887).\par
\par
This shouldn\rquote t affect you when developing on `localhost`, but if you develop remotely like [described here](https://github.com/facebook/create-react-app/issues/2271), you will see this error in the browser after enabling the `proxy` option:\par
\par
> Invalid Host header\par
\par
To work around it, you can specify your public development host in a file called `.env.development` in the root of your project:\par
\par
```\par
HOST=mypublicdevhost.com\par
```\par
\par
If you restart the development server now and load the app from the specified host, it should work.\par
\par
If you are still having issues or if you\rquote re using a more exotic environment like a cloud editor, you can bypass the host check completely by adding a line to `.env.development.local`. **Note that this is dangerous and exposes your machine to remote code execution from malicious websites:**\par
\par
```\par
# NOTE: THIS IS DANGEROUS!\par
# It exposes your machine to attacks from the websites you visit.\par
DANGEROUSLY_DISABLE_HOST_CHECK=true\par
```\par
\par
We don\rquote t recommend this approach.\par
\par
### Configuring the Proxy Manually\par
\par
> Note: this feature is available with `react-scripts@2.0.0` and higher.\par
\par
If the `proxy` option is **not** flexible enough for you, you can get direct access to the Express app instance and hook up your own proxy middleware.\par
\par
You can use this feature in conjunction with the `proxy` property in `package.json`, but it is recommended you consolidate all of your logic into `src/setupProxy.js`.\par
\par
First, install `http-proxy-middleware` using npm or Yarn:\par
\par
```bash\par
$ npm install http-proxy-middleware --save\par
$ # or\par
$ yarn add http-proxy-middleware\par
```\par
\par
Next, create `src/setupProxy.js` and place the following contents in it:\par
\par
```js\par
const proxy = require('http-proxy-middleware');\par
\par
module.exports = function(app) \{\par
  // ...\par
\};\par
```\par
\par
You can now register proxies as you wish! Here's an example using the above `http-proxy-middleware`:\par
\par
```js\par
const proxy = require('http-proxy-middleware');\par
\par
module.exports = function(app) \{\par
  app.use(proxy('/api', \{ target: '{{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK http://localhost:5000/ }}{\fldrslt{http://localhost:5000/\ul0\cf0}}}}\f1\fs22 ' \}));\par
\};\par
```\par
\par
> **Note:** You do not need to import this file anywhere. It is automatically registered when you start the development server.\par
\par
> **Note:** This file only supports Node's JavaScript syntax. Be sure to only use supported language features (i.e. no support for Flow, ES Modules, etc).\par
\par
> **Note:** Passing the path to the proxy function allows you to use globbing and/or pattern matching on the path, which is more flexible than the express route matching.\par
\par
