## Running Tests\par
\par
> Note: this feature is available with `react-scripts@0.3.0` and higher.<br>\par
\par
> [Read the migration guide to learn how to enable it in older projects!](https://github.com/facebook/create-react-app/blob/master/CHANGELOG.md#migrating-from-023-to-030)\par
\par
Create React App uses [Jest](https://facebook.github.io/jest/) as its test runner. To prepare for this integration, we did a [major revamp](https://facebook.github.io/jest/blog/2016/09/01/jest-15.html) of Jest so if you heard bad things about it years ago, give it another try.\par
\par
Jest is a Node-based runner. This means that the tests always run in a Node environment and not in a real browser. This lets us enable fast iteration speed and prevent flakiness.\par
\par
While Jest provides browser globals such as `window` thanks to [jsdom](https://github.com/tmpvar/jsdom), they are only approximations of the real browser behavior. Jest is intended to be used for unit tests of your logic and your components rather than the DOM quirks.\par
\par
We recommend that you use a separate tool for browser end-to-end tests if you need them. They are beyond the scope of Create React App.\par
\par
### Filename Conventions\par
\par
Jest will look for test files with any of the following popular naming conventions:\par
\par
- Files with `.js` suffix in `__tests__` folders.\par
- Files with `.test.js` suffix.\par
- Files with `.spec.js` suffix.\par
\par
The `.test.js` / `.spec.js` files (or the `__tests__` folders) can be located at any depth under the `src` top level folder.\par
\par
We recommend to put the test files (or `__tests__` folders) next to the code they are testing so that relative imports appear shorter. For example, if `App.test.js` and `App.js` are in the same folder, the test just needs to `import App from './App'` instead of a long relative path. Colocation also helps find tests more quickly in larger projects.\par
\par
### Command Line Interface\par
\par
When you run `npm test`, Jest will launch in the watch mode. Every time you save a file, it will re-run the tests, just like `npm start` recompiles the code.\par
\par
The watcher includes an interactive command-line interface with the ability to run all tests, or focus on a search pattern. It is designed this way so that you can keep it open and enjoy fast re-runs. You can learn the commands from the \ldblquote Watch Usage\rdblquote  note that the watcher prints after every run:\par
\par
![Jest watch mode](http://facebook.github.io/jest/img/blog/15-watch.gif)\par
\par
### Version Control Integration\par
\par
By default, when you run `npm test`, Jest will only run the tests related to files changed since the last commit. This is an optimization designed to make your tests run fast regardless of how many tests you have. However it assumes that you don\rquote t often commit the code that doesn\rquote t pass the tests.\par
\par
Jest will always explicitly mention that it only ran tests related to the files changed since the last commit. You can also press `a` in the watch mode to force Jest to run all tests.\par
\par
Jest will always run all tests on a [continuous integration](#continuous-integration) server or if the project is not inside a Git or Mercurial repository.\par
\par
### Writing Tests\par
\par
To create tests, add `it()` (or `test()`) blocks with the name of the test and its code. You may optionally wrap them in `describe()` blocks for logical grouping but this is neither required nor recommended.\par
\par
Jest provides a built-in `expect()` global function for making assertions. A basic test could look like this:\par
\par
```js\par
import sum from './sum';\par
\par
it('sums numbers', () => \{\par
  expect(sum(1, 2)).toEqual(3);\par
  expect(sum(2, 2)).toEqual(4);\par
\});\par
```\par
\par
All `expect()` matchers supported by Jest are [extensively documented here](https://facebook.github.io/jest/docs/en/expect.html#content).<br>\par
You can also use [`jest.fn()` and `expect(fn).toBeCalled()`](https://facebook.github.io/jest/docs/en/expect.html#tohavebeencalled) to create \ldblquote spies\rdblquote  or mock functions.\par
\par
### Testing Components\par
\par
There is a broad spectrum of component testing techniques. They range from a \ldblquote smoke test\rdblquote  verifying that a component renders without throwing, to shallow rendering and testing some of the output, to full rendering and testing component lifecycle and state changes.\par
\par
Different projects choose different testing tradeoffs based on how often components change, and how much logic they contain. If you haven\rquote t decided on a testing strategy yet, we recommend that you start with creating simple smoke tests for your components:\par
\par
```js\par
import React from 'react';\par
import ReactDOM from 'react-dom';\par
import App from './App';\par
\par
it('renders without crashing', () => \{\par
  const div = document.createElement('div');\par
  ReactDOM.render(<App />, div);\par
\});\par
```\par
\par
This test mounts a component and makes sure that it didn\rquote t throw during rendering. Tests like this provide a lot of value with very little effort so they are great as a starting point, and this is the test you will find in `src/App.test.js`.\par
\par
When you encounter bugs caused by changing components, you will gain a deeper insight into which parts of them are worth testing in your application. This might be a good time to introduce more specific tests asserting specific expected output or behavior.\par
\par
If you\rquote d like to test components in isolation from the child components they render, we recommend using [`shallow()` rendering API](http://airbnb.io/enzyme/docs/api/shallow.html) from [Enzyme](http://airbnb.io/enzyme/). To install it, run:\par
\par
```sh\par
npm install --save enzyme enzyme-adapter-react-16 react-test-renderer\par
```\par
\par
Alternatively you may use `yarn`:\par
\par
```sh\par
yarn add enzyme enzyme-adapter-react-16 react-test-renderer\par
```\par
\par
As of Enzyme 3, you will need to install Enzyme along with an Adapter corresponding to the version of React you are using. (The examples above use the adapter for React 16.)\par
\par
The adapter will also need to be configured in your [global setup file](#initializing-test-environment):\par
\par
#### `src/setupTests.js`\par
\par
```js\par
import \{ configure \} from 'enzyme';\par
import Adapter from 'enzyme-adapter-react-16';\par
\par
configure(\{ adapter: new Adapter() \});\par
```\par
\par
> Note: Keep in mind that if you decide to "eject" before creating `src/setupTests.js`, the resulting `package.json` file won't contain any reference to it. [Read here](#initializing-test-environment) to learn how to add this after ejecting.\par
\par
Now you can write a smoke test with it:\par
\par
```js\par
import React from 'react';\par
import \{ shallow \} from 'enzyme';\par
import App from './App';\par
\par
it('renders without crashing', () => \{\par
  shallow(<App />);\par
\});\par
```\par
\par
Unlike the previous smoke test using `ReactDOM.render()`, this test only renders `<App>` and doesn\rquote t go deeper. For example, even if `<App>` itself renders a `<Button>` that throws, this test will pass. Shallow rendering is great for isolated unit tests, but you may still want to create some full rendering tests to ensure the components integrate correctly. Enzyme supports [full rendering with `mount()`](http://airbnb.io/enzyme/docs/api/mount.html), and you can also use it for testing state changes and component lifecycle.\par
\par
You can read the [Enzyme documentation](http://airbnb.io/enzyme/) for more testing techniques. Enzyme documentation uses Chai and Sinon for assertions but you don\rquote t have to use them because Jest provides built-in `expect()` and `jest.fn()` for spies.\par
\par
Here is an example from Enzyme documentation that asserts specific output, rewritten to use Jest matchers:\par
\par
```js\par
import React from 'react';\par
import \{ shallow \} from 'enzyme';\par
import App from './App';\par
\par
it('renders welcome message', () => \{\par
  const wrapper = shallow(<App />);\par
  const welcome = <h2>Welcome to React</h2>;\par
  // expect(wrapper.contains(welcome)).toBe(true);\par
  expect(wrapper.contains(welcome)).toEqual(true);\par
\});\par
```\par
\par
All Jest matchers are [extensively documented here](http://facebook.github.io/jest/docs/en/expect.html).<br>\par
Nevertheless you can use a third-party assertion library like [Chai](http://chaijs.com/) if you want to, as described below.\par
\par
Additionally, you might find [jest-enzyme](https://github.com/blainekasten/enzyme-matchers) helpful to simplify your tests with readable matchers. The above `contains` code can be written more simply with jest-enzyme.\par
\par
```js\par
expect(wrapper).toContainReact(welcome);\par
```\par
\par
To enable this, install `jest-enzyme`:\par
\par
```sh\par
npm install --save jest-enzyme\par
```\par
\par
Alternatively you may use `yarn`:\par
\par
```sh\par
yarn add jest-enzyme\par
```\par
\par
Import it in [`src/setupTests.js`](#initializing-test-environment) to make its matchers available in every test:\par
\par
```js\par
import 'jest-enzyme';\par
```\par
\par
### Using Third Party Assertion Libraries\par
\par
We recommend that you use `expect()` for assertions and `jest.fn()` for spies. If you are having issues with them please [file those against Jest](https://github.com/facebook/jest/issues/new), and we\rquote ll fix them. We intend to keep making them better for React, supporting, for example, [pretty-printing React elements as JSX](https://github.com/facebook/jest/pull/1566).\par
\par
However, if you are used to other libraries, such as [Chai](http://chaijs.com/) and [Sinon](http://sinonjs.org/), or if you have existing code using them that you\rquote d like to port over, you can import them normally like this:\par
\par
```js\par
import sinon from 'sinon';\par
import \{ expect \} from 'chai';\par
```\par
\par
and then use them in your tests like you normally do.\par
\par
### Initializing Test Environment\par
\par
> Note: this feature is available with `react-scripts@0.4.0` and higher.\par
\par
If your app uses a browser API that you need to mock in your tests or if you just need a global setup before running your tests, add a `src/setupTests.js` to your project. It will be automatically executed before running your tests.\par
\par
For example:\par
\par
#### `src/setupTests.js`\par
\par
```js\par
const localStorageMock = \{\par
  getItem: jest.fn(),\par
  setItem: jest.fn(),\par
  clear: jest.fn(),\par
\};\par
global.localStorage = localStorageMock;\par
```\par
\par
> Note: Keep in mind that if you decide to "eject" before creating `src/setupTests.js`, the resulting `package.json` file won't contain any reference to it, so you should manually create the property `setupTestFrameworkScriptFile` in the configuration for Jest, something like the following:\par
\par
> ```js\par
> "jest": \{\par
>   // ...\par
>   "setupTestFrameworkScriptFile": "<rootDir>/src/setupTests.js"\par
>  \}\par
> ```\par
\par
### Focusing and Excluding Tests\par
\par
You can replace `it()` with `xit()` to temporarily exclude a test from being executed.<br>\par
Similarly, `fit()` lets you focus on a specific test without running any other tests.\par
\par
