## Making a Progressive Web App\par
\par
The production build has all the tools necessary to generate a first-class\par
[Progressive Web App](https://developers.google.com/web/progressive-web-apps/),\par
but **the offline/cache-first behavior is opt-in only**. By default,\par
the build process will generate a service worker file, but it will not be\par
registered, so it will not take control of your production web app.\par
\par
In order to opt-in to the offline-first behavior, developers should look for the\par
following in their [`src/index.js`](src/index.js) file:\par
\par
```js\par
// If you want your app to work offline and load faster, you can change\par
// unregister() to register() below. Note this comes with some pitfalls.\par
// Learn more about service workers: {{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK http://bit.ly/CRA-PWA }}{\fldrslt{http://bit.ly/CRA-PWA\ul0\cf0}}}}\f1\fs22\par
serviceWorker.unregister();\par
```\par
\par
As the comment states, switching `serviceWorker.unregister()` to\par
`serviceWorker.register()` will opt you in to using the service worker.\par
\par
### Why Opt-in?\par
\par
Offline-first Progressive Web Apps are faster and more reliable than traditional web pages, and provide an engaging mobile experience:\par
\par
- All static site assets are cached so that your page loads fast on subsequent visits, regardless of network connectivity (such as 2G or 3G). Updates are downloaded in the background.\par
- Your app will work regardless of network state, even if offline. This means your users will be able to use your app at 10,000 feet and on the subway.\par
- On mobile devices, your app can be added directly to the user's home screen, app icon and all. This eliminates the need for the app store.\par
\par
However, they [can make debugging deployments more challenging](https://github.com/facebook/create-react-app/issues/2398) so, starting with Create React App 2, service workers are opt-in.\par
\par
The [`workbox-webpack-plugin`](https://developers.google.com/web/tools/workbox/modules/workbox-webpack-plugin)\par
is integrated into production configuration,\par
and it will take care of generating a service worker file that will automatically\par
precache all of your local assets and keep them up to date as you deploy updates.\par
The service worker will use a [cache-first strategy](https://developers.google.com/web/fundamentals/instant-and-offline/offline-cookbook/#cache-falling-back-to-network)\par
for handling all requests for local assets, including\par
[navigation requests](https://developers.google.com/web/fundamentals/primers/service-workers/high-performance-loading#first_what_are_navigation_requests)\par
for your HTML, ensuring that your web app is consistently fast, even on a slow\par
or unreliable network.\par
\par
### Offline-First Considerations\par
\par
If you do decide to opt-in to service worker registration, please take the\par
following into account:\par
\par
1. Service workers [require HTTPS](https://developers.google.com/web/fundamentals/getting-started/primers/service-workers#you_need_https),\par
   although to facilitate local testing, that policy\par
   [does not apply to `localhost`](http://stackoverflow.com/questions/34160509/options-for-testing-service-workers-via-http/34161385#34161385).\par
   If your production web server does not support HTTPS, then the service worker\par
   registration will fail, but the rest of your web app will remain functional.\par
\par
1. Service workers are [not supported](https://jakearchibald.github.io/isserviceworkerready/#moar)\par
   in older web browsers. Service worker registration [won't be attempted](src/registerServiceWorker.js)\par
   on browsers that lack support.\par
\par
1. The service worker is only enabled in the [production environment](#deployment),\par
   e.g. the output of `npm run build`. It's recommended that you do not enable an\par
   offline-first service worker in a development environment, as it can lead to\par
   frustration when previously cached assets are used and do not include the latest\par
   changes you've made locally.\par
\par
1. If you _need_ to test your offline-first service worker locally, build\par
   the application (using `npm run build`) and run a simple http server from your\par
   build directory. After running the build script, `create-react-app` will give\par
   instructions for one way to test your production build locally and the [deployment instructions](#deployment) have\par
   instructions for using other methods. _Be sure to always use an\par
   incognito window to avoid complications with your browser cache._\par
\par
1. Users aren't always familiar with offline-first web apps. It can be useful to\par
   [let the user know](https://developers.google.com/web/fundamentals/instant-and-offline/offline-ux#inform_the_user_when_the_app_is_ready_for_offline_consumption)\par
   when the service worker has finished populating your caches (showing a "This web\par
   app works offline!" message) and also let them know when the service worker has\par
   fetched the latest updates that will be available the next time they load the\par
   page (showing a "New content is available; please refresh." message). Showing\par
   this messages is currently left as an exercise to the developer, but as a\par
   starting point, you can make use of the logic included in [`src/registerServiceWorker.js`](src/registerServiceWorker.js), which\par
   demonstrates which service worker lifecycle events to listen for to detect each\par
   scenario, and which as a default, just logs appropriate messages to the\par
   JavaScript console.\par
\par
1. By default, the generated service worker file will not intercept or cache any\par
   cross-origin traffic, like HTTP [API requests](#integrating-with-an-api-backend),\par
   images, or embeds loaded from a different domain.\par
\par
### Progressive Web App Metadata\par
\par
The default configuration includes a web app manifest located at\par
[`public/manifest.json`](public/manifest.json), that you can customize with\par
details specific to your web application.\par
\par
When a user adds a web app to their homescreen using Chrome or Firefox on\par
Android, the metadata in [`manifest.json`](public/manifest.json) determines what\par
icons, names, and branding colors to use when the web app is displayed.\par
[The Web App Manifest guide](https://developers.google.com/web/fundamentals/engage-and-retain/web-app-manifest/)\par
provides more context about what each field means, and how your customizations\par
