## Deployment\par
\par
`npm run build` creates a `build` directory with a production build of your app. Set up your favorite HTTP server so that a visitor to your site is served `index.html`, and requests to static paths like `/static/js/main.<hash>.js` are served with the contents of the `/static/js/main.<hash>.js` file.\par
\par
### Static Server\par
\par
For environments using [Node](https://nodejs.org/), the easiest way to handle this would be to install [serve](https://github.com/zeit/serve) and let it handle the rest:\par
\par
```sh\par
npm install -g serve\par
serve -s build\par
```\par
\par
The last command shown above will serve your static site on the port **5000**. Like many of [serve](https://github.com/zeit/serve)\rquote s internal settings, the port can be adjusted using the `-p` or `--port` flags.\par
\par
Run this command to get a full list of the options available:\par
\par
```sh\par
serve -h\par
```\par
\par
### Other Solutions\par
\par
You don\rquote t necessarily need a static server in order to run a Create React App project in production. It works just as fine integrated into an existing dynamic one.\par
\par
Here\rquote s a programmatic example using [Node](https://nodejs.org/) and [Express](http://expressjs.com/):\par
\par
```javascript\par
const express = require('express');\par
const path = require('path');\par
const app = express();\par
\par
app.use(express.static(path.join(__dirname, 'build')));\par
\par
app.get('/', function(req, res) \{\par
  res.sendFile(path.join(__dirname, 'build', 'index.html'));\par
\});\par
\par
app.listen(9000);\par
```\par
\par
The choice of your server software isn\rquote t important either. Since Create React App is completely platform-agnostic, there\rquote s no need to explicitly use Node.\par
\par
The `build` folder with static assets is the only output produced by Create React App.\par
\par
However this is not quite enough if you use client-side routing. Read the next section if you want to support URLs like `/todos/42` in your single-page app.\par
\par
### Serving Apps with Client-Side Routing\par
\par
If you use routers that use the HTML5 [`pushState` history API](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/History_API#Adding_and_modifying_history_entries) under the hood (for example, [React Router](https://github.com/ReactTraining/react-router) with `browserHistory`), many static file servers will fail. For example, if you used React Router with a route for `/todos/42`, the development server will respond to `localhost:3000/todos/42` properly, but an Express serving a production build as above will not.\par
\par
This is because when there is a fresh page load for a `/todos/42`, the server looks for the file `build/todos/42` and does not find it. The server needs to be configured to respond to a request to `/todos/42` by serving `index.html`. For example, we can amend our Express example above to serve `index.html` for any unknown paths:\par
\par
```diff\par
 app.use(express.static(path.join(__dirname, 'build')));\par
\par
-app.get('/', function (req, res) \{\par
+app.get('/*', function (req, res) \{\par
   res.sendFile(path.join(__dirname, 'build', 'index.html'));\par
 \});\par
```\par
\par
If you\rquote re using [Apache HTTP Server](https://httpd.apache.org/), you need to create a `.htaccess` file in the `public` folder that looks like this:\par
\par
```\par
    Options -MultiViews\par
    RewriteEngine On\par
    RewriteCond %\{REQUEST_FILENAME\} !-f\par
    RewriteRule ^ index.html [QSA,L]\par
```\par
\par
It will get copied to the `build` folder when you run `npm run build`.\par
\par
If you\rquote re using [Apache Tomcat](http://tomcat.apache.org/), you need to follow [this Stack Overflow answer](https://stackoverflow.com/a/41249464/4878474).\par
\par
Now requests to `/todos/42` will be handled correctly both in development and in production.\par
\par
On a production build, and when you've [opted-in](#why-opt-in),\par
a [service worker](https://developers.google.com/web/fundamentals/primers/service-workers/) will automatically handle all navigation requests, like for\par
`/todos/42`, by serving the cached copy of your `index.html`. This\par
service worker navigation routing can be configured or disabled by\par
[`eject`ing](#npm-run-eject) and then modifying the\par
[`navigateFallback`](https://github.com/GoogleChrome/sw-precache#navigatefallback-string)\par
and [`navigateFallbackWhitelist`](https://github.com/GoogleChrome/sw-precache#navigatefallbackwhitelist-arrayregexp)\par
options of the `SWPreachePlugin` [configuration](../config/webpack.config.prod.js).\par
\par
When users install your app to the homescreen of their device the default configuration will make a shortcut to `/index.html`. This may not work for client-side routers which expect the app to be served from `/`. Edit the web app manifest at [`public/manifest.json`](public/manifest.json) and change `start_url` to match the required URL scheme, for example:\par
\par
```js\par
  "start_url": ".",\par
```\par
\par
### Building for Relative Paths\par
\par
By default, Create React App produces a build assuming your app is hosted at the server root.<br>\par
To override this, specify the `homepage` in your `package.json`, for example:\par
\par
```js\par
  "homepage": "{{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK http://mywebsite.com/relativepath }}{\fldrslt{http://mywebsite.com/relativepath\ul0\cf0}}}}\f1\fs22 ",\par
```\par
\par
This will let Create React App correctly infer the root path to use in the generated HTML file.\par
\par
**Note**: If you are using `react-router@^4`, you can root `<Link>`s using the `basename` prop on any `<Router>`.<br>\par
More information [here](https://reacttraining.com/react-router/web/api/BrowserRouter/basename-string).<br>\par
<br>\par
For example:\par
\par
```js\par
<BrowserRouter basename="/calendar"/>\par
<Link to="/today"/> // renders <a href="/calendar/today">\par
```\par
\par
#### Serving the Same Build from Different Paths\par
\par
> Note: this feature is available with `react-scripts@0.9.0` and higher.\par
\par
If you are not using the HTML5 `pushState` history API or not using client-side routing at all, it is unnecessary to specify the URL from which your app will be served. Instead, you can put this in your `package.json`:\par
\par
